So first of all, if we're trying to check the quality of our model, the most common things are, first of all, when we're mapping to the scheme of our source data, suppose that we're loading from your Snowflake database and we're trying to target very specific columns or trying to target very specific table names.

980
02:01:28,959 --> 02:01:42,559
Very, very common error that we'll see when we're designing our model or designing our queries is that we might be, let's say, we have a column that is called part number and we're calling it part-no.

981
02:01:42,559 --> 02:01:49,599
It's a very common issue when it comes to just model quality, query quality, et cetera.

982
02:01:49,599 --> 02:01:56,000
The other thing is we saw this before when we were looking in our graph marks.

983
02:01:56,000 --> 02:01:59,919
So suppose I'm modifying this query that we have here.

984
02:01:59,919 --> 02:02:01,160
That is working.

985
02:02:01,160 --> 02:02:05,919
You see I'm targeting this Accenture underscore movie underscore data.

986
02:02:05,919 --> 02:02:12,839
But suppose instead I target this one, which has a very, very similar name, but obviously is wrong.

987
02:02:15,639 --> 02:02:21,039
And it's obviously wrong because I can try the query against it and not going to see the class that we made.

988
02:02:21,039 --> 02:02:26,160
There's two very similarly named models that we can get completed.

989
02:02:26,160 --> 02:02:36,600
So when we're talking here about missing, wrong, or confusing the target ontology, that's what we're talking about where we're either picking the wrong one because of a confusing definition.

990
02:02:36,600 --> 02:02:39,479
We aren't picking one at all, et cetera.

991
02:02:39,479 --> 02:02:45,440
Another important note is checking the data quality.

992
02:02:45,440 --> 02:03:09,520
Any time there is an enterprise big data deployment, doesn't matter whether it's Anzo or whether it's Snowflake with any tool, there is going to be some issue down the line of data quality, whether it comes to someone in some lab having a typo, whether it comes down to something else, maybe some issues related to data quality.

993
02:03:09,520 --> 02:03:17,639
So when it comes to that, we can use our validation steps to validate, OK, this data is as expected.

994
02:03:17,639 --> 02:03:25,440
I'm personally of the belief that there should always be some human level of data validation when it comes to enterprise level deployments.

995
02:03:25,440 --> 02:03:29,600
But these ultimately come down to business preferences.

996
02:03:29,600 --> 02:03:32,440
But these are some good notes here.

997
02:03:32,440 --> 02:03:36,279
Avoid the usage of different predicates for the same relationship.

998
02:03:36,279 --> 02:03:54,119
So that's if, for example, if we look at our movie example where we have actor ID, movie ID, if these are all just primary keys with essentially the field ID, could we just reuse the same predicate in all those situations?

999
02:03:54,119 --> 02:04:02,960
Because if you recall, if we go back here and we look, suppose that we're making our canonical model.

1000
02:04:05,839 --> 02:04:09,199
Let's say I add a property here, and I just call this ID.

1001
02:04:09,199 --> 02:04:10,479
This isn't movie ID.

1002
02:04:10,479 --> 02:04:12,520
This isn't canonical ID.

1003
02:04:12,520 --> 02:04:17,880
Obviously, the string here is, the range here is going to be a string.

1004
02:04:17,880 --> 02:04:24,000
I can put this on movie, and I can also say actors also have an ID.

1005
02:04:24,000 --> 02:04:36,079
And now I get to reuse the same exact URI, but I don't have to reinvent the wheel just because I have a second class.

1006
02:04:36,079 --> 02:04:42,279
And so that's what we're talking about there, where we're trying to avoid using different predicates when it's not necessary.

1007
02:04:42,279 --> 02:04:43,239
It has the same range.

1008
02:04:43,239 --> 02:04:44,839
It has the same purpose.

1009
02:04:44,839 --> 02:04:48,119
Let's just reuse it across the different classes.

1010
02:04:48,119 --> 02:04:51,200
There's nothing wrong with that.

1011
02:04:51,200 --> 02:04:58,880
Another important note here is just detecting inconsistencies in data.

1012
02:04:58,880 --> 02:05:13,079
And these are things like we're ingesting data from a file, and we're expecting a delimiter of a comma, but actually, in this one row, there's actually a delimiter of a semicolon.

1013
02:05:13,079 --> 02:05:19,679
Things that counter expectations can often derail a project more than you might expect.

1014
02:05:19,679 --> 02:05:21,600
So keep track of these things.

1015
02:05:21,600 --> 02:05:27,920
And also, obviously, we want to keep in mind our custom business logic and making sure that the business rules are always being followed.

1016
02:05:30,959 --> 02:05:33,519
So here's an example.

1017
02:05:33,519 --> 02:05:46,679
We have a variety of queries that are designed to check various things based on, in this case, in this example, the user has created their own class to basically do quality control.

1018
02:05:46,679 --> 02:05:51,440
So they have a class in ontology.

1019
02:05:51,440 --> 02:05:58,399
So in this case, we have this quality control model on the right, where we see we have some data validation warnings.

1020
02:05:58,399 --> 02:06:05,959
And so there's basically classes that we created called missing class warning, multi-value constraint violation, et cetera.

1021
02:06:05,959 --> 02:06:17,200
And so these queries, all they're doing is they're going to create a new instance of these various violations and warnings based on what it's seeing from the actual source data.

1022
02:06:17,200 --> 02:06:19,359
This is kind of a neat way to do that.

1023
02:06:19,359 --> 02:06:37,160
